            <p>Charles Babbage (1791â€“1871) was an English mathematician, philosopher, inventor, and mechanical engineer. He is credited with conceptualizing the first automatic mechanical computer, known as the Analytical Engine. His design was a precursor to modern computers and laid the foundation for the field of computing.</p>
        </div>

        <div id="timeline">
            <h2>Timeline of Achievements</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>1791:</strong> Charles Babbage is born on December 26 in London, England.</li>
                <li><strong>1821:</strong> Babbage designs the Difference Engine, an automatic mechanical calculator for solving polynomial equations.</li>
                <li><strong>1832:</strong> Babbage publishes his ideas for the Analytical Engine, a more advanced mechanical computer that could perform any calculation.</li>
                <li><strong>1834:</strong> The British government commissions Babbage to build a working Difference Engine.</li>
                <li><strong>1871:</strong> Charles Babbage passes away on October 18 at the age of 79. His ideas and designs continue to influence modern computing.</li>
            </ul>
